 But he comes to Washington well prepared for the kind of back-room political arm-twisting that will be required to persuade a divided Congress to pass it.
 Many Democrats in Congress, including some in the powerful Illinois delegation, are uncommitted.
 Mr Daley's talents have been summoned, insiders say, to convince moderate Democrats to back the agreement.
 Mr Clinton may be banking on Mr Daley's union ties to help the Nafta effort.
 However, Mr Daley, by pushing Nafta, runs the risk of alienating his union supporters.
